Ι sodes·z'ntro‚ consequar jam te. “ But in, I pray you, I will follow presently.” The behaviour of Pamphilus in this scene is most faithfully copied from nature. Being shocked at the discovery he has made, he leaves the house in great anguish, which, though he wishes to dissemble, he is unable to conceal. He cannot receive his mother as he ought, or give an answer of above two words: and feeling himself unfit for conversation or company, he finds means to remove Sostrata and Parmeno as soon as possible. When any unex- pected grief takes hold of us, witnesses lay a constraint on our behaviour, and we are apt to wish to be alone, in order to deliver our- selves up entirely to the natural emotions of the mind.
